# overview

> A codebase-local memory graph for AI coding agents.

eshp stores long-term project knowledge as plain-text `.eshp` files in an `eshp/`
folder alongside your code. A SQLite graph backs them for fast querying. Everything
commits to git.

## Why it exists

Coding agents lose context at session boundaries. Project knowledge gets buried in
chat history or locked inside proprietary tools. eshp solves this by keeping memory
in your repo — version-controlled, readable, and tool-agnostic.

Core goals:
- Keep long-term project memory in git, not in proprietary agents
- Persist structured knowledge across session boundaries and tool changes
- Make agent decisions readable and auditable (see what was recalled and scanned)
- Warm-start coding sessions with compact graph-structured context instead of
  re-explaining the codebase from scratch each time

## Who it's for

Any developer using AI coding agents on a codebase longer than a single session —
especially when switching between agents or resuming work after a break.

## Inspiration

Loosely inspired by the A-mem paper on agent memory architectures.

